[In the past 24 hours, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 98 cases and 2 deaths as compared with yesterday's 24 hour period (20-21 Mar 2020) when there were 147 newly confirmed cases. Over the past few days, the case count has oscillated from below to above 100 newly confirmed cases per day Daegu continues to stand out as a focal point for transmission with 72.1% of the total cases reported followed by Gyeongbuk with 14.1% of the total cases reported. Looking at recent activity, Daegu reported 43.9% of the newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by Gyeonggi with 16.3% of the newly confirmed cases. Looking at the graphics on the English language website from 22 Mar 2020, one can see how the cumulative curve of reported cases seems to be approaching a plateau In Daegu and to a slightly lesser extent in Gyeongbuk, but is still very much continuing a fairly rapid daily climb in Seoul and Gyeonggi (see https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=&bid=0030 for tables and graphs. There is a table showing the age specific fatality ratios, showing similar data with what was seen in China. Ages 80 and older had a 10.5% fatality ratio; 70-79, 6.2%; 60-69, 1.5%; 50-59, 0.4%; 40-49, 0.1%; and 30-39, 0.1%. There were no reported deaths in the 0-29 year olds, with almost 2400 confirmed cases in the 20-29 year old age group.

Similar to what is being seen in China, Korea is identifying increasing numbers of imported cases coming from Europe (and I would suspect they are beginning to notice a similar trend in people coming from the USA). Like in China, there is strict surveillance and follow-up of these individuals, reversing the pattern of the western countries strengthening screenings of individuals from South Korea and China. Obvious concerns re: initiating new clusters that might escape into the community.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7124533,195 - Mod.MPP]

