C. Iran: 20 610 cases, 1556 deaths
Date: Sat 21 Mar 2020 9:09 AM GST
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-iran/irans-coronavirus-deaths-rise-to-1556-infections-exceed-20000-health-ministry-idUSKBN2180BU


Iran's death toll from the coronavirus [COVID-19] outbreak rose by more than 100 to 1556 on Saturday [21 Mar 2020] and the total number of people infected now exceeds 20 000, a health ministry official said.

Iran, one of the countries most affected by the pandemic outside China, had on Friday [20 Mar 2020] reported a death toll of 1433 and a total number of confirmed infections of 19 644.

The total number of people diagnosed with the disease stood at 20 610 on Saturday [21 Mar 2020], health ministry spokesman Kianoush Jahanpour said on state TV. Jahanpur warned that coronavirus cases would rise steeply unless people refrain from traveling during the 2-week Iranian New Year holiday, which started yesterday [20 Mar 2020].

"If people take it lightly and think that the coronavirus outbreak is over, and if urban and inter-city traffic and gatherings in resorts and natural parks increase ... then in 1 to 2 weeks we will see a new peak of the disease," he said according to the semi-official ISNA [Iranian Students News Agency] news agency.

President Hassan Rouhani said on Saturday [21 Mar 2020] that social distancing measures to combat the coronavirus outbreak, including travel restrictions, will apply for only 2 to 3 weeks, expecting the crisis to ease by then. Iran "has to do everything necessary to return economic production to normal," he said in comments broadcast on state TV. He also accused "counter-revolutionaries" of plotting to shut down economic production.

[Byline: Maher Chmatyelli; editing: Louise Heavens, David Holmes]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the 24 hours from 20 to 21 Mar 2020, the number of cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Iran grew from 19 644 to 20 610 an increase of 966 newly confirmed cases but 21.9% less than in the previous 24 hours (1237). The number of deaths has also increased from 1433 to 1556 an increase of 123 deaths in the 24 hour period, a 17.4% decrease in daily deaths reported from the previous 24 hours (149). It is a 1st observation, but we can hope this is a starting trend.

As I mentioned yesterday (21 Mar 2020), the significant translocation of the population for the holidays is of concern as it may lead to continued intra country/provincial exportations of the virus.

A map of Iran showing provinces can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/iran/iran-political-map.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7124533,128. - Mod.MPP]

