[5] US Health Weather Map
Date: Sat 21 Mar 2020
Source: US Health Weather Map[edited]
https://healthweather.us/


Overview
--------
The US Health Weather Map is a visualization of seasonal illness linked to fever -- specifically influenza-like illness. The aggregate, anonymized data visualized here is a product of Kinsa's network of Smart Thermometers and the accompanying mobile applications. Kinsa is providing this map and associated charts as a public service.

The map shows 2 key data points: (1) the illness levels we are currently observing, and (2) the degree to which those levels are higher than the typical levels we expect to see at this point in the flu season. (Details on how we calculate this are available in our technical approach document.) We believe this latter data point -- which we're calling "atypical illness", may in some cases be connected to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Please note: We are not stating that this data represent COVID-19 activity. However, we would expect to pick up higher-than-anticipated levels of flu-like symptoms in our data in areas where the pandemic is affecting large numbers of people. Taken together with other data points, we believe this data may be a helpful early indicator of where and how quickly the virus is spreading.

--
Communicated by:
William N Coxe Jr JD
Department of Experimental Statistics
Louisiana State University
36 Martin D Woodin Hall
Baton Rouge, Louisiana
USA
<wcoxe1@lsu.edu>

[Our thanks to William Coxe Jr for sharing this link with us. A visualization using ILI (influenza-like illness) surveillance data as a surrogate means of following atypical ILI activity. In checking the daily reports by country, the USA started reporting more cases of SARS-CoV-2 infected individuals.

Comparing this map with the map put out by Florida today (21 Mar 2020) https://www.orlandosentinel.com/coronavirus/fl-ne-florida-coronavirus-cases-by-the-numbers-20200320-4dnircjpyjbl5g44ihlep6dpou-htmlstory.html#nt=standard-embed, I looked at Polk County (inland from Pinellas county on the Gulf Coast, midway up the state), the US Health Weather map identifies Polk county as having had an outbreak of atypical ILI, currently 3% above expected rates, with an increase starting around 4 Mar 2020, peaking on 19 Mar 2020, and dropping off precipitously since 19 Mar 2020. In contrast the Florida state statistics show 10 positive tests out of 171 specimens received, with 21 still pending. What isn't available is the date of the specimens and the date of onset of illness of people who submitted specimens for testing to compare and see if there may have been a "missed" outbreak when testing wasn't available. - Mod.MPP]

